ssing day, urban social movements and their radical strategies to resist climate injustice often remain concealed from sight. Contributors to this volume ask how would it be to look at the politics of urban loss-and-damage not from the highly securitized zones of climate summits, but from favelas in Rio de Janeiro, flood-prone communities in São Paulo, urban gardens in Naples, or neighborhoods resisting climate gentrification in New York City? This book explores diverse worlds and praxis of urban social movements resisting the rising tides of climate crisis and social injustice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aConflict and Peace. 4aContemporary Society. 4aEnvironment and Sustainability. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh  aClimate Justice, Radical adaptation.  aGrassroots movements, Urban social movements.  aLoss and Damage.1 aArmiero, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmiero, Marco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarbosa, Natasha Augusto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerruti, Gilda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoda, Chad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastán Broto, Vanesa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawson, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Rosa, Salvatore Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenrique, Karen Paiva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators